    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-12-27T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-12-27T16:00:00-05:00" n="726"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d726">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">832.2546/12–2751: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Brazil</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rio de Janeiro</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-12-27T19:00:00-02:00"
                            >December 27, 1951—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>813. For Assistant Secretary Miller. Mytel 811, Dec 26, 6 p. m.<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d726fn1">Not printed.</note>
                    <gloss target="#t_FonMin1">FonMin</gloss> told me this afternoon with great
                    apparent satisfaction of action taken Dec 22 by Natl Security Council in
                    authorizing negots with US Govt agreements re supply strategic materials. He
                    said slowness with which action in particular (1) monazite, (2) manganese, and
                    (3) uranium,<note n="2" xml:id="d726fn2">For documentation relating to the
                        efforts of the United States to negotiate an agreement with Brazil
                        concerning uranium, see <ref target="frus1951v01#pg_685">vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, pp. 685</ref> ff.</note> had progressed had
                    been matter of great concern to him. Now he has been authorized by Pres to carry
                    these negots to conclusion, he optimistic they may be entirely cleared up before
                    end Jan. Final agreements will have be approved by Pres, but will not have again
                    go through Security Council and bureaucratic machinery. Monazite he believes is
                    capable particularly early action. He has already set up comite in <gloss
                        target="#t_FonOff1">FonOff</gloss> to iron out remaining difficulties re
                    urucum managanese contract and expects Gov Matto Grosso in Rio early next week.
                    It probably state Matto Grosso’s desire for larger royalties will be made at
                    expense Chama brothers. Difficulties purely of internal order and <gloss
                        target="#t_FonMin1">FonMin</gloss> stated no objection had been voiced in
                    any quarter to US obtaining supplies manganese required. Prices all these
                    commodities he indicated wld be matter for negot.</p>
                <p>At mtg this afternoon <gloss target="#t_FonMin1">FonMin</gloss> again reiterated
                    it was desire Pres Vargas himself and admin in gen to “go along” with US in all
                    these questions. He deplored ponderous nature Braz bureaucracy and said he felt
                    SAT’s clearance for action by Security Council wld greatly facilitate progress.
                    At Security Council mtg <gloss target="#t_MinFin1">MinFin</gloss> Lafer spoke in
                    support his proposal.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
